Question:
A jeweller has 12 pieces of chain, each with two links. He wants to make one big closed necklace of them, as shown. To do this he has to open some links (and close them afterwards). What is the smallest number of links he has to open? See image.

Options:
A: \(8\)
B: \(9\)
C: \(10\)
D: \(11\)
E: \(12\)

message.content:
Each piece is a 2-link closed chain. We have 12 such pieces, so 24 links total. We must rearrange them into one closed necklace of 24 links.

Every time we open a link that belongs to a piece, that piece becomes a smaller chain of its remaining intact links plus possibly some opened links used as connectors. To join 12 separate components into 1 closed loop, we need at least 11 joins (edges in a tree on 12 vertices), plus 1 more join to close the loop → at least 12 joins. Each join requires opening at least one link. So we need at least 12 opened links; and this is achievable by opening exactly one link in each 2-link piece and using it to connect to the growing chain.

Thus, the minimum is 12.

Answer:E
